%D9%8E%D9%91%D8%B1%D9%8E"}},"translations":null,"definition":{"source":"wiktextract","senses":[{"pos":"verb","gloss":"to roll, to roll up, to coil, to wind"},{"pos":"verb","gloss":"to make round"},{"pos":"verb","gloss":"to clench"},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"camel saddle"},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"furnace, smelting furnace, forge"},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"bellows"},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"plural of كُرَة (kura, “ball”)","tags":["form-of","plural"]},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"plural of كُورَة (kūra)","tags":["form-of","plural"]}]},"etymology":{"source":"wiktextract","text":"An early Semitic borrowing, ultimately derived from Sumerian 𒄥 (gur, “to twist, to wind, to turn”).\n\nLikely through Aramaic from Akkadian 𒆠𒉈 (/⁠kuru⁠/, “crucible, kiln, brazier; log, thick reed; short reed mat, collection of reeds”), likely coined from Sumerian 𒄥 (gur, “a bundle”), hence a place of burning bundles of firewood or tinder. The sense of a saddle originally stems from a bundle or mat rolled and placed for cushioning; a specified sense natively coined from Akkadian 𒄀𒆤𒈣 (/⁠kuru⁠/, “short reed mat, collection or roll of reeds; a woven thing”), from Sumerian 𒄥 (gur, “to twist, to wind, to turn”).\n\nSee the etymology of the corresponding lemma form."},"ipa":null,"lanes_definition":null,"classical_definitions":null}